Here's the standard approach:

## 1. Define each theme as a `ResourceDictionary`

```xml
<!-- Resources/Themes/LightTheme.xaml -->
<ResourceDictionary xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
                    xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
                    x:Class="MyApp.Resources.Themes.LightTheme">
    <Color x:Key="PageBackground">#FFFFFF</Color>
    <Color x:Key="TextPrimary">#1A1A1A</Color>
    <Color x:Key="Accent">#0078D4</Color>
</ResourceDictionary>
```

```xml
<!-- Resources/Themes/DarkTheme.xaml -->
<ResourceDictionary ...>
    <Color x:Key="PageBackground">#1E1E1E</Color>
    <Color x:Key="TextPrimary">#E0E0E0</Color>
    <Color x:Key="Accent">#4CC2FF</Color>
</ResourceDictionary>
```

```xml
<!-- Resources/Themes/HighContrastTheme.xaml -->
<ResourceDictionary ...>
    <Color x:Key="PageBackground">#000000</Color>
    <Color x:Key="TextPrimary">#FFFFFF</Color>
    <Color x:Key="Accent">#FFFF00</Color>
</ResourceDictionary>
```

## 2. Use `DynamicResource` in your pages/styles

This is the critical part — `StaticResource` won't update at runtime.

```xml
<ContentPage BackgroundColor="{DynamicResource PageBackground}">
    <Label Text="Hello" TextColor="{DynamicResource TextPrimary}" />
</ContentPage>
```

## 3. Create a theme service to swap dictionaries

```csharp
public enum AppTheme { Light, Dark, HighContrast }

public static class ThemeService
{
    public static void ApplyTheme(AppTheme theme)
    {
        var mergedDicts = Application.Current!.Resources.MergedDictionaries;

        // Remove the current theme dictionary (always the last one added)
        if (mergedDicts.Count > 0)
            mergedDicts.Clear();

        mergedDicts.Add(theme switch
        {
            AppTheme.Dark         => new Resources.Themes.DarkTheme(),
            AppTheme.HighContrast => new Resources.Themes.HighContrastTheme(),
            _                     => new Resources.Themes.LightTheme(),
        });

        // Persist the choice
        Preferences.Set("app_theme", theme.ToString());
    }

    public static void LoadSavedTheme()
    {
        var saved = Preferences.Get("app_theme", nameof(AppTheme.Light));
        if (Enum.TryParse<AppTheme>(saved, out var theme))
            ApplyTheme(theme);
    }
}
```

## 4. Set the default theme on startup

```csharp
// App.xaml.cs
public App()
{
    InitializeComponent();
    ThemeService.LoadSavedTheme();
}
```

## 5. Wire up the settings page

```xml
<Picker x:Name="ThemePicker" Title="Theme"
        ItemsSource="{Binding Themes}"
        SelectedIndexChanged="OnThemeChanged" />
```

```csharp
public partial class SettingsPage : ContentPage
{
    public List<string> Themes { get; } = ["Light", "Dark", "High Contrast"];

    void OnThemeChanged(object? sender, EventArgs e)
    {
        var theme = ThemePicker.SelectedIndex switch
        {
            1 => AppTheme.Dark,
            2 => AppTheme.HighContrast,
            _ => AppTheme.Light,
        };
        ThemeService.ApplyTheme(theme);
    }
}
```

**Key takeaways:**
- **`DynamicResource`** everywhere you reference theme colors — this is what makes live switching work.
- Each theme must define the **same keys** so swapping dictionaries is seamless.
- `Preferences` persists the user's choice across app restarts.
